==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fother
<hw>Foth"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>fother</ets>, <ets>foder</ets>, AS. <ets>f⟦omac⟧<?/er</ets> a
cartload; akin to G. <ets>fuder</ets> a cartload, a unit of measure,
OHG. <ets>fuodar</ets>, D. <ets>voeder</ets>, and perh. to E.
<ets>fathom</ets>, or cf. Skr. <ets>p⟦amac⟧tr⟦amac⟧</ets> vessel, dish.
Cf. <er>Fodder</er> a fother.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A wagonload; a
load of any sort.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of dung full many a <qex>fother</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>See <er>Fodder</er>, a unit of weight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fother</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fother
<hw>Foth"er</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Fothered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Fothering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. <er>Fodder</er> food, and
G. <ets>f⟦uum⟧ttern</ets>, <ets>futtern</ets>, to cover within or
without, to line. ⟦root⟧75.]</ety> <def>To stop (a leak in a ship at
sea) by drawing under its bottom a thrummed sail, so that the pressure
of the water may force it into the crack.</def>
<rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fotive</ent>⟦br⟧
